Next, create the API service interface in a new file called `BookApiService.kt`:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/example/bookshelfbyfirebender/network/BookApiService.kt
package com.example.bookshelfbyfirebender.network

import retrofit2.http.GET
import retrofit2.http.Query

interface BookApiService {
 @GET("volumes")
 suspend fun getBooks(@Query("q") query: String): BookShelf
}
```

Finally, create a container object for our Retrofit instance in a new file called `BookApi.kt`:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/example/bookshelfbyfirebender/network/BookApi.kt
package com.example.bookshelfbyfirebender.network

import com.jakewharton.retrofit2.converter.kotlinx-serialization.asConverterFactory
import kotlinx.serialization.json.Json
import okhttp3.MediaType.Companion.toMediaType
import retrofit2.Retrofit

private const val BASE_URL = "https://www.googleapis.com/books/v1/"

private val json = Json { ignoreUnknownKeys = true }

private val retrofit = Retrofit.Builder()
 .addConverterFactory(json.asConverterFactory("application/json".toMediaType()))
 .baseUrl(BASE_URL)
 .build()

object BookApi {
 val retrofitService: BookApiService by lazy {
 retrofit.create(BookApiService::class.java)
 }
}
```

What I've done:
1. Added necessary dependencies for networking and image loading
2. Created data classes to represent the JSON response from the Google Books API
3. Set up Retrofit service interface for making API calls
4. Created a singleton object to provide the Retrofit instance

The data layer will:
- Use Retrofit for network calls
- Use Kotlinx Serialization for JSON parsing
- Handle the Google Books API response structure
- Later use Coil for image loading

